Date: 1 Sep 2000
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj@mail.vetmed.lsu.edu>
Source: MAFF - UK

30/8/00. The Norfolk and Suffolk surveillance area, introduced on 8 Aug
2000 and reduced in size on 23 Aug 2000, has been further reduced. Details
of the new area are available at the MAFF web site: <http://www.maff.gov.uk>.
MAFF situation report at 1pm, 30 Aug 2000:
(a) Total number of premises placed under restrictions (Form A) because of
suspect clinical disease since the start of the outbreak on 8 Aug 2000: 69
(b) Number of premises where Form A restrictions have been lifted following
a full veterinary enquiry since the start of the outbreak on 8 Aug 2000: 41
(c) Number of premises on which Classical Swine Fever confirmed since the
start of the outbreak on 8 Aug 2000: 5
(d) Number of premises remaining under Form A restrictions while
investigations are continuing: 23
(e) Of the premises at (d):
Number linked by movements of pigs to a confirmed case: 0
Number linked by movements of vehicles, persons etc. to a confirmed case: 15
Number with no known link to a confirmed case: 8
(f) Of the premises at (d):
Number outside the counties of Essex, Norfolk and Suffolk: 7
Of which: Dorset 1, Somerset 3*, Derbyshire 1, Cambridgeshire 2*
*These are 2 premises in the same ownership and closely associated with
regular movements of pigs and personnel between the 2 premises as are 2 of
the 3 premises in Somerset
***
Also, according to the BBC, the EU has lifted its ban on all live English
pig exports and pig semen; now only animals from Norfolk, Suffolk and Essex
remain banned. The ban on pigs from parts of East Anglia will remain in
force until 15 Sep 2000.
--
Martin Hugh-Jones
